<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-329-995  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 329 995.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 13 1989 v23 n6 p99(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ten causes of project busts. (Taking Charge) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bienkowski, Danek.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A newly initiated business project is usually healthy andvigorous, staffed with members full of enthusiasm, but as timegoes by the project often goes awry, the budge soars out ofcontrol, unforeseen difficulties delay completion of key tasks andteam members are over-scheduled and overworked.andP;  The 10 majorcauses of project failure are: the project is seen as a solutionin search of a problem, only the project team is interested in theend result, no one is in charge, the project plan lacks structure,the project plan lacks detail, the project is under-budgeted,insufficient nonfinancial resources are allocated to the project,the project is not tracked against its plan, the project team isnot communicating and the project deviates from its originalgoals.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Project ManagementMethodsFailureBusinessAnalysisBusiness Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>